OL,3,C'They were equal' - The women at the
OL,4,Ccoalface of the miners' strike
OL,6,F"They weren't asking for money, they
OL,7,Fwere asking to fight to keep a job, to
OL,8,Fkeep a job for future generations."
OL,10,FHeather had an idea to support hard-up
OL,11,Ffamilies and at Easington Colliery
OL,12,FClub she set up the region's first
OL,13,Fminers' food kitchen.
OL,15,F"The first thing on people's minds is
OL,16,F'what about the children? How are we
OL,17,Fgoing to feed the bairns?'"
OL,19,FShe set about ringing her mother and
OL,20,Fher friends and put notices up in the
OL,21,Fshop.
