OL,3,C'They were equal' - The women at the
OL,4,Ccoalface of the miners' strike
OL,6,FOne of those women for whose life was
OL,7,Fchanged by her own course of action
OL,8,Fduring the strike was Ann Lilburn,
OL,9,Ffrom Northumberland, who became the
OL,10,Fchair of the National Women Against
OL,11,FPit Closures (WAPC).
OL,13,FUntil miners walked out she had never
OL,14,Fspoken at a village hall. But by the
OL,15,Fsummer of 1984, she was leading a
OL,16,Frally of 23,000 women through London.
OL,1,W h7}h7}j7}h7}h7}                 G6/10
